      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is the legal doctrine that insists the Constitution must be interpreted according to the meaning it held at the time it was ratified. The core justification is that the Constitution is a fixed text, and judges should not impose their own evolving policy preferences onto it. By adhering to original intent or original public meaning, judges ensure that the law remains stable and predictable, respecting the will of the founders. This prevents judicial activism, which is essentially judges legislating from the bench.",
